<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-178-112  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 178 112.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  March 20 1989 n530 p31(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fluke raps cuts in tech-transfer funds. (John Fluke ManufacturingCompany Inc. Chmn John Fluke Jr.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Nostrand, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>John Fluke Manufacturing Co Chmn John Fluke Jr.andP;  says that theAmerican Electronics Association (AEA) condemns the Bushadministration's decision to provide no funds for the newtechnology-transfer program of the Commerce Department's NationalInstitute of Standard and Technology (NIST).andP;  TRW Inc VP oftechnical resources Arden Bemont agrees with Fluke, adding thatthe present budget threatens the continuity and productivity ofthe NIST science and engineering programs on which technologytransfer programs must build.andP;  The executives are alsodisappointed that the new budget of $155.6 million for the NIST(plus $4.1 million for a new Technology Administration) barelyoffsets the impact of inflation.andP;  The NIST manufacturing andtechnology-transfer programs are intended to promote internationalcompetitiveness and help domestic industry develop andcommercialize new technologies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. National Institute of Standards and TechnologyUnited States. Department of CommerceTechnology TransferBudgetingGoals and ObjectivesImpact AnalysisAmerican Electronics AssociationInternational Trade.andO;Person:    Fluke, John M., Jr. (attitudes); Bement, Arden (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>